he cruiser {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Akashi||2}} as his flagship and eight [[Kaba-class destroyer|''Kaba''-class destroyers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyJapanese.htm#dd|title=Japanese Navy, IJN, World War 1|publisher=|access-date=21 December 2016}}</ref> {{sfn|Halpern|1995|p=393}} The Japanese fleet was nominally independent, but carried out operations under the direction of the [[Royal Navy]] command on Malta, primarily in escort operations for transport and troopship convoys and in [[anti-submarine warfare]] operations.{{sfn|Halpern|1995|p=393}}\n\n''Sakaki'' was damaged by the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] [[U-boat]] {{ship|SM|U-27|Austria-Hungary|2}} on 11 June 1917 off of [[Crete]] with the loss of 68{{#tag:ref|Authors Evan & Peattie say that 59 were KIA{{sfn|Evans|Peattie|2015|p=169}}|group=\"A\"}} of her 92 crewmen, including her skipper.{{sfn|Evans|Peattie|2015|p=169}} {{sfn|Tucker|Mary|2005|p=1069}} {{sfn|Saxon|2000|p=62}} She was salvaged and repaired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/japanese_destroyers.htm|title=Japanese Destroyers|publisher=|access-date=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyJapanese.htm|title=Japanese Navy, IJN, World War 1|publisher=|access-date=21 December 2016}}</ref> The ashes of the dead Japanese sailors were returned to Japan by the Imperial Japanese Navy.{{sfn|''New-York Tribune'', December 2,|1917|p=4}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Kaba class destroyer}}\n* French [[Arabe-class destroyer]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=\"A\"}}\n{{reflist|20em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|last=Evans|first=David C. |last2=Peattie|first2= Mark | authorlink2=  Mark Peattie| title = Kaigun: Strategy, Tactics, and Technology in the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1887\u20131941|year=2015| publisher = [[United States Naval Institute|Naval Institute Press]]| isbn=978-1-61251-425-3 }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|last=Halpern|first=Paul G. | authorlink = Paul G. Halpern| title = A Naval History of World War I|year=1995| publisher = UCL Press| isbn= 978-1-85728-498-0}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|last=Howarth|first=Stephen | title = The Fighting Ships of the Rising Sun: The Drama of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1895\u20131945|year=1983| publisher = Atheneum| isbn= 978-0-689-11402-1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|last=Jentschura|first=Hansgeorg |last2=Jung|first2=Dieter |last3=Mickel|first3=Peter | title = Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869\u20131945|year=1977| publisher = [[United States Naval Institute|Naval Institute Press]]| isbn= 978-0-87021-893-4}}\n*{{cite news |ref={{SfnRef|''New-York Tribune'', December 2,|1917}}|date= December 2, 1917|title= Our Allies in their Common Cause|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83030214/1917-12-02/ed-1/?sp=4&r=-0.134,-0.082,1.233,0.583,0|newspaper=[[New-York Tribune]]|publisher= |location=New York|issn=1941-0646 |oclc=9405688|pages=1\u201310|accessdate= December 8, 2019 }}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Saxon|first= Timothy D. |date= Winter 2000|title=Anglo-Japanese Naval Cooperation, 1914\u20131918|journal= [[Naval War College Review]]|volume= 53|issue=1 |pages=62\u201392|url=https://digital-commons.usnwc.edu/nwc-review/vol53/iss1/4/|access-date=7 December 2019 |publisher=[[Naval War College|United States Naval War College]]|issn=0028-1484|lccn=75617787|oclc=01779130}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C|last2=Mary |first2=Priscilla | authorlink = Spencer C. Tucker| title = World War I: Encyclopedia, Volume 1|year=2005| publisher = ABC-CLIO| isbn=978-1-85109-420-2}}\n=== Further reading ===\n*{{cite book\n | last = Cocker\n | first = Maurice\n | year = 1983\n | title = Destroyers of the Royal Navy, 1893\u20131981\n | publisher = Ian Allan\n | location =\n | isbn = 978-0-7110-1075-8\n}}\n \n\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{Kaba class destroyers}}\n{{WWIJapaneseShips}}\n\n{{DEFAU